{"title_page": "Jo Butterfield", "text_new": "{{short description|British parasport athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = yellow\n| image = \n| image_size = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels. !-->\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| full_name = Joanna Shuni Butterfield, {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}}\n| nickname = \n| nationality = British\n| residence =  \n| birth_date =  {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|3|19}}\n| birth_place =  [[Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height =   <!-- {{convert| |cm|ftin}} (2012) !-->\n| weight =  <!-- {{convert| |kg|lb}} (2012) !-->\n| website =  <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !-->\n| country = \n| sport = Athletics\n| event = Club throw, Discus\n| collegeteam = \n| club = Forth Valley Flyers<br/>Red Star\n| team = \n| turnedpro = \n| retired = \n| coach = Philip Peat\n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = \n| paralympics = \n| highestranking = \n| pb = {{nowrap|Discus: 10.08m}}<br/>{{nowrap|Club: 22.81m}}\n|medaltemplates= \n{{MedalSport | Track and field (athletics)}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] |[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus throw \u2013 F52]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F31/32/51]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Joanna Shuni Butterfield''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 19 March 1979) is a British parasport athlete who competes in the F51 [[club throw|club]] and [[discus throw]].<ref name=\"paralympics\">{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=1294324 |title=Butterfield, Joanna|accessdate=25 October 2015|publisher=IPC}}</ref> In 2014 Butterfield set a European record in the club while winning the event at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]]. The following year she added the World title at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Qatar, securing a place at the [[2016 Paralympic Games]].\n\n==Personal history==\nButterfield was born in [[Yorkshire]], England in 1979, but later moved to Glasgow in Scotland.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/34629723|title=IPC World Championships: Jo Butterfield wins GB's fifth gold|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=24 October 2015|author=Hudson, Elizabeth}}</ref> In 2011, she was diagnosed with a spinal tumor which resulted in her being paralysed below the waist.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\"/>\n\n==Sports career==\nDuring her rehabilitation at a spinal unit in Glasgow, Butterfield was introduced to the sport of [[wheelchair rugby]].<ref name=\"crushers bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caledoniancrushers.co.uk/player/jo-butterfield/|title=Jo Butterfield|publisher=caledoniancrushers.co.uk|accessdate=25 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713232929/http://www.caledoniancrushers.co.uk/player/jo-butterfield/|archive-date=13 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In early 2012 she joined the Caledonian Crushers, and later became their vice-captain.<ref name=\"crushers bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/13263954.It_s_game_on_for_wheelchair_rugby_contest/|title=It's Game on for wheelchair rugby contest|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=19 September 2013|author=Sutton, Matty|work=Evening Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Butterfield was classified as a F51 disability athlete and began competing in regional meets in both the discus and club throw events.<ref name=\"Powerof10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepowerof10.info/athletes/profile.aspx?athleteid=660074|title=Joanna Butterfield|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=thepowerof10.info}}</ref> In August that year she was selected for the Great Britain team to compete at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]]. There she competed in the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|F32/51 club throw]], and set a new European record with a distance of 17.68m winning gold in all British podium alongside [[Josie Pearson]] and [[Gemma Prescott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/28899572|title=IPC European Championships: Jo Butterfield wins club throw gold|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=22 August 2015|author=Hudson, Elizabeth}}</ref> That season she also competed at the SDS Championships in Perth and threw personal bests in both the discus (9.79m) and the club (19.50m), winning gold in both events.<ref name=\"Powerof10\"/>\n\nThe following year Butterfield travelled to Dubai to take part in the Fazaa International, the first [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] Grand Prix of the year. In the F32/33/51 discus she threw 8.87m to win the competition and beat the previous F51 European record by 27 centimetres.<ref name=\"Dubai Prix\">{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/featured/maria-lyle-jo-butterfield-set-world-records-dubai-18110/|title=Maria Lyle and Jo Butterfield set world records in Dubai |accessdate=25 October 2015|date=26 February 2015|publisher=athleticsweekly.com}}</ref> She also improved on her European record in the club with a throw of 19.69 which saw her take gold.<ref name=\"Dubai Prix\"/> In July Butterfield competed in her third IPC Grand Prix of the year, held at [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park|Olympic Park]] in London. A throw of 21.50 in the club not only gave her the title, but improved on her European title to take her within 40&nbsp;cm of American [[Rachael Morrison]]'s world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishdisabilitysport.com/sds/index.cfm/news/latest-news1/anniversary-games-sunday-26-july-at-olympic-park-london/|title=Anniversary Games \u2013 Sunday 26 July at Olympic Park, London|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=26 July 2015|publisher=scottishdisabilitysport.com}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Morrison was Butterfield's main rival when the two met at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Doha. In the club Butterfield threw 21.44 to set a championship record and push her American rival into silver medal place.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\"/> But it was Morrison on top when they met a few days later in the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|T52 discus throw]], with Butterfield coming third behind Morrison and Mexico's [[Leticia Ochoa Delgado]]. Though Butterfield's distance of 8.96m was a new European record for a F51 athlete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/eng/at/ATR173A_QA2015ATW607101ENG.htm|title=Results \u2013 Women's Discus throw F52 Final|accessdate=27 October 2015|date=27 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref>\n\nButterfield was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2017 New Year Honours for services to field athletics.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61803|supp=y|page=N16|date=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=joanna-butterfield|old_id=1294324|name=Joanna Butterfield}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butterfield, Joanna}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bristol]]\n[[Category:British female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Disabled track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen with disabilities]]\n[[Category:British disabled sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Scottish disabled sportspeople]]\n[[Category:British female club throwers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People with paraplegia]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British parasport athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = yellow\n| name = Joanna Shuni Butterfield<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]</small>\n| image = \n| image_size = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels. !-->\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| fullname = \n| nickname = \n| nationality = British\n| residence =  \n| birth_date =  {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|3|19}}\n| birth_place =  [[Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height =   <!-- {{convert| |cm|ftin}} (2012) !-->\n| weight =  <!-- {{convert| |kg|lb}} (2012) !-->\n| website =  <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !-->\n| country = \n| sport = Athletics\n| event = Club throw, Discus\n| collegeteam = \n| club = Forth Valley Flyers<br/>Red Star\n| team = \n| turnedpro = \n| retired = \n| coach = Philip Peat\n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = \n| paralympics = \n| highestranking = \n| pb = {{nowrap|Discus: 10.08m}}<br/>{{nowrap|Club: 22.81m}}\n|medaltemplates= \n{{MedalSport | Track and field (athletics)}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] |[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus throw \u2013 F52]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F51]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw \u2013 F31/32/51]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Joanna Shuni Butterfield''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 19 March 1979) is a British parasport athlete who competes in the F51 [[club throw|club]] and [[discus throw]].<ref name=\"paralympics\">{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=1294324 |title=Butterfield, Joanna|accessdate=25 October 2015|publisher=IPC}}</ref> In 2014 Butterfield set a European record in the club while winning the event at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]]. The following year she added the World title at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Qatar, securing a place at the [[2016 Paralympic Games]].\n\n==Personal history==\nButterfield was born in [[Yorkshire]], England in 1979, but later moved to Glasgow in Scotland.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/34629723|title=IPC World Championships: Jo Butterfield wins GB's fifth gold|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=24 October 2015|author=Hudson, Elizabeth}}</ref> In 2011, she was diagnosed with a spinal tumor which resulted in her being paralysed below the waist.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\"/>\n\n==Sports career==\nDuring her rehabilitation at a spinal unit in Glasgow, Butterfield was introduced to the sport of [[wheelchair rugby]].<ref name=\"crushers bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caledoniancrushers.co.uk/player/jo-butterfield/|title=Jo Butterfield|publisher=caledoniancrushers.co.uk|accessdate=25 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713232929/http://www.caledoniancrushers.co.uk/player/jo-butterfield/|archive-date=13 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In early 2012 she joined the Caledonian Crushers, and later became their vice-captain.<ref name=\"crushers bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/13263954.It_s_game_on_for_wheelchair_rugby_contest/|title=It's Game on for wheelchair rugby contest|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=19 September 2013|author=Sutton, Matty|work=Evening Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Butterfield was classified as a F51 disability athlete and began competing in regional meets in both the discus and club throw events.<ref name=\"Powerof10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepowerof10.info/athletes/profile.aspx?athleteid=660074|title=Joanna Butterfield|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=thepowerof10.info}}</ref> In August that year she was selected for the Great Britain team to compete at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]]. There she competed in the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|F32/51 club throw]], and set a new European record with a distance of 17.68m winning gold in all British podium alongside [[Josie Pearson]] and [[Gemma Prescott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/28899572|title=IPC European Championships: Jo Butterfield wins club throw gold|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=22 August 2015|author=Hudson, Elizabeth}}</ref> That season she also competed at the SDS Championships in Perth and threw personal bests in both the discus (9.79m) and the club (19.50m), winning gold in both events.<ref name=\"Powerof10\"/>\n\nThe following year Butterfield travelled to Dubai to take part in the Fazaa International, the first [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] Grand Prix of the year. In the F32/33/51 discus she threw 8.87m to win the competition and beat the previous F51 European record by 27 centimetres.<ref name=\"Dubai Prix\">{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/featured/maria-lyle-jo-butterfield-set-world-records-dubai-18110/|title=Maria Lyle and Jo Butterfield set world records in Dubai |accessdate=25 October 2015|date=26 February 2015|publisher=athleticsweekly.com}}</ref> She also improved on her European record in the club with a throw of 19.69 which saw her take gold.<ref name=\"Dubai Prix\"/> In July Butterfield competed in her third IPC Grand Prix of the year, held at [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park|Olympic Park]] in London. A throw of 21.50 in the club not only gave her the title, but improved on her European title to take her within 40&nbsp;cm of American [[Rachael Morrison]]'s world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishdisabilitysport.com/sds/index.cfm/news/latest-news1/anniversary-games-sunday-26-july-at-olympic-park-london/|title=Anniversary Games \u2013 Sunday 26 July at Olympic Park, London|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=26 July 2015|publisher=scottishdisabilitysport.com}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Morrison was Butterfield's main rival when the two met at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Doha. In the club Butterfield threw 21.44 to set a championship record and push her American rival into silver medal place.<ref name=\"BBC 24 Oct\"/> But it was Morrison on top when they met a few days later in the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|T52 discus throw]], with Butterfield coming third behind Morrison and Mexico's [[Leticia Ochoa Delgado]]. Though Butterfield's distance of 8.96m was a new European record for a F51 athlete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/eng/at/ATR173A_QA2015ATW607101ENG.htm|title=Results \u2013 Women's Discus throw F52 Final|accessdate=27 October 2015|date=27 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref>\n\nButterfield was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2017 New Year Honours for services to field athletics.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61803|supp=y|page=N16|date=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055535/http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&gender=all&name=Butterfield&fname=Joanna Joanna Butterfield at the International Paralympic Committee]\n* {{IPC athlete|1294324|Joanna Butterfield}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butterfield, Joanna}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bristol]]\n[[Category:British female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Disabled track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen with disabilities]]\n[[Category:British disabled sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Scottish disabled sportspeople]]\n[[Category:British female club throwers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People with paraplegia]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo_Butterfield"}
{"title_page": "Euroseeds", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| caption = \n| logo = [[File:Euroseeds logo.jpg|240px]]\n| formation = November 2000\n| type = Non-profit [[trade association]]\n| status = \n| purpose = Representing members in the [[plant breeding]], [[agriculture]], and [[biotechnology]] industries\n| headquarters = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = R\u00e9gis Fournier\n| leader_title2 = Secretary General\n| leader_name2 = Garlich von Essen\n| name = Euroseeds\n| abbreviation = Euroseeds\n| location = \n| region_served = [[European Union]], [[European Economic Area]]\n| website = [http://www.euroseeds.eu www.euroseeds.eu]\n}}\n\n''Euroseeds'' is a [[trade association]] for the [[seed]] industry in the [[European Union]] and the [[European Economic Area]]. An umbrella organization of national seed associations and individual [[Seed company|seed companies]], their members represent all aspects of the European seed industry including research, [[plant breeding]], and the production and [[marketing]] of seeds of agricultural, horticultural and ornamental plant species. It was founded in November 2000 and was granted the legal status of international non-profit International Association (AISBL) according to [[Belgian law]] in April 2002. Its headquarters are located in [[Brussels]], Belgium.\n\n== History ==\nFollowing increasing inter-organizational cooperation begun in 1998, four separate European seed [[trade associations]] were merged into a single organization, at that time ESA, in 2000. They were COSEMCO (seed trade, founded in 1961), ASSOPOMAC (potato breeders, founded in 1964), AMUFOC ([[forage]] seed production, founded in 1970) and COMASSO (plant breeders, founded in 1977).\n\n== Functions and scope of activities ==\n{{Prose|section|date=September 2012}}\nAccording to the Euroseeds' [[mission statement]], it is \"the voice of the European seed industry and represents companies and national organisations active in research, breeding, production and marketing of seeds of agricultural, horticultural and ornamental plant species.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroseeds.org/what-we-do|title=ESA European Seed Association.  ESA Mission Statement|access-date=2012-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019034721/http://www.euroseeds.org/what-we-do|archive-date=2011-10-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> Euroseeds serves as a [[lobby group]] for all seed industry-related issues in the European Union and European Economic Area and specifically on:\n* Seed marketing\n* Plant breeding \n* [[Intellectual property right]]s such as plant breeders's rights and [[biotech]] patents\n* Plant and seed health such as [[phytosanitary]] rules and seed treatments\n* [[Biodiversity]] and access to genetic resources\n* Land use and food production\n* Competitiveness of the EU agri-food chain\n\nIt also works on collective problems of its membership such as market access in other countries.\n\nEuroseeds represents the European seed industry via the European institutions ([[European Commission]], [[European Parliament]], [[Council of the European Union|Council of Ministers]]) as well as the EU's [[Community Plant Variety Office]] (CPVO) and numerous European and international bodies and organisations. \n\n===Observer status===\n\nEuroseeds has been granted observer status with the following organizations:{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n* International Seed Federation (ISF)\n* [[International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants]] (UPOV)\n* [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD)\n* International Seed Testing Association (ISTA)\n* [[International Plant Protection Convention]] (IPPC)\n* [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO)\n\n== Events ==\nEach year in October, Euroseeds holds its Congress which is attended by around 900 participants from industry as well as policy makers, representatives of the European Commission, the EU's Community Plant Variety Office, and international organizations such as UPOV, FAO OECD, the International Seed Testing Association (ISTA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esa.conceptum.eu/|title=ESA Annual Meeting 2018 - Home Page|website=esa.conceptum.eu}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\nEuroseeds represents over 100 members out of which 35 are national seed associations from EU Members States and the wider Europe. Next to these association members, Euroseeds' membership also comprises 52 individual direct company members, both multi-national as well as specialised small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), and 24 associate members from seed related industries, media and academia and from outside of Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroseeds.org/who-we-are/members|title=ESA European Seed Association. Members|access-date=2012-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918040859/http://www.euroseeds.org/who-we-are/members|archive-date=2010-09-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Euroseeds presidents ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 2000\u20132003 || Anthony Keeling, Elsoms Seeds Ltd. (UK)\n|-\n| 2003\u20132006 || Sten Moberg, [[Lantm\u00e4nnen|Sval\u00f6f Weibull]] (Sweden)\n|-\n| 2006\u20132009 || Francois Desprez, Florimond Desprez (France)\n|-\n| 2009\u20132012 || Christoph Amberger, [[KWS Saat|KWS Saat AG]] (Germany)\n|-\n| 2012\u20132015||Gerard Backx, HZPC (the Netherlands)\n|-\n| 2015\u20132018||Nigel Moore, KWS SAAT SE (UK)\n|-\n|2018-2021\n|R\u00e9gis Fournier, MAS Seeds (France)\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\nThe following contain material on the activities of the Euroseeds:\n*Bodiguel, Luc and Cardwell, Michael (2009). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U8htC86rSmUC&q=%22European+Seed+Association%22+#v=snippet&q=%22European%20Seed%20Association%22&f=false ''The Regulation of Genetically Modified Organisms: Comparative Approaches'']. Oxford University Press\n*Jolly, Adam and Philpott, Jeremy (2012). [https://books.google.com/books?id=ywU11-rBiCEC&q=%22European+Seed+Association%22#v=snippet&q=%22European%20Seed%20Association%22&f=false ''The Handbook of European Intellectual Property Management'']. Kogan Page Publishers\n*Maggioni, L. and Lipman, E. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=xlN7YKcDR7oC&q=%22European+Seed+Association%22#v=snippet&q=%22European%20Seed%20Association%22&f=false ''Report of the ECPGR Network Coordinating Groups: First Meeting, 29-31 March 2006, Bonn, Germany'']. Bioversity International\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.euroseeds.eu/|Euroseeds official website}}\n\n[[Category:Pan-European trade and professional organizations]]\n[[Category:Agricultural organisations based in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Seed associations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2000]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| caption = \n| formation = November 2000\n| type = Non-profit [[trade association]]\n| status = \n| purpose = Representing members in the [[plant breeding]], [[agriculture]], and [[biotechnology]] industries\n| headquarters = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = R\u00e9gis Fournier\n| leader_title2 = Secretary General\n| leader_name2 = Garlich von Essen\n| name = Euroseeds\n| abbreviation = Euroseeds\n| location = \n| region_served = [[European Union]], [[European Economic Area]]\n| website = [http://www.euroseeds.eu www.euroseeds.eu]\n}}\n\n''Euroseeds'' is a [[trade association]] for the [[seed]] industry in the [[European Union]] and the [[European Economic Area]]. An umbrella organization of national seed associations and individual [[Seed company|seed companies]], their members represent all aspects of the European seed industry including research, [[plant breeding]], and the production and [[marketing]] of seeds of agricultural, horticultural and ornamental plant species. It was founded in November 2000 and was granted the legal status of international non-profit International Association (AISBL) according to [[Belgian law]] in April 2002. Its headquarters are located in [[Brussels]], Belgium.\n\n== History ==\nFollowing increasing inter-organizational cooperation begun in 1998, four separate European seed [[trade associations]] were merged into a single organization, at that time ESA, in 2000. They were COSEMCO (seed trade, founded in 1961), ASSOPOMAC (potato breeders, founded in 1964), AMUFOC ([[forage]] seed production, founded in 1970) and COMASSO (plant breeders, founded in 1977).\n\n== Functions and scope of activities ==\n{{Prose|section|date=September 2012}}\nAccording to the Euroseeds' [[mission statement]], it is \"the voice of the European seed industry and represents companies and national organisations active in research, breeding, production and marketing of seeds of agricultural, horticultural and ornamental plant species.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroseeds.org/what-we-do|title=ESA European Seed Association.  ESA Mission Statement|access-date=2012-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019034721/http://www.euroseeds.org/what-we-do|archive-date=2011-10-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> Euroseeds serves as a [[lobby group]] for all seed industry-related issues in the European Union and European Economic Area and specifically on:\n* Seed marketing\n* Plant breeding \n* [[Intellectual property right]]s such as plant breeders's rights and [[biotech]] patents\n* Plant and seed health such as [[phytosanitary]] rules and seed treatments\n* [[Biodiversity]] and access to genetic resources\n* Land use and food production\n* Competitiveness of the EU agri-food chain\n\nIt also works on collective problems of its membership such as market access in other countries.\n\nEuroseeds represents the European seed industry via the European institutions ([[European Commission]], [[European Parliament]], [[Council of the European Union|Council of Ministers]]) as well as the EU's [[Community Plant Variety Office]] (CPVO) and numerous European and international bodies and organisations. \n\n===Observer status===\n\nEuroseeds has been granted observer status with the following organizations:{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n* International Seed Federation (ISF)\n* [[International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants]] (UPOV)\n* [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD)\n* International Seed Testing Association (ISTA)\n* [[International Plant Protection Convention]] (IPPC)\n* [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO)\n\n== Events ==\nEach year in October, Euroseeds holds its Congress which is attended by around 900 participants from industry as well as policy makers, representatives of the European Commission, the EU's Community Plant Variety Office, and international organizations such as UPOV, FAO OECD, the International Seed Testing Association (ISTA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esa.conceptum.eu/|title=ESA Annual Meeting 2018 - Home Page|website=esa.conceptum.eu}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\nEuroseeds represents over 100 members out of which 35 are national seed associations from EU Members States and the wider Europe. Next to these association members, Euroseeds' membership also comprises 52 individual direct company members, both multi-national as well as specialised small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), and 24 associate members from seed related industries, media and academia and from outside of Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroseeds.org/who-we-are/members|title=ESA European Seed Association. Members|access-date=2012-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918040859/http://www.euroseeds.org/who-we-are/members|archive-date=2010-09-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Euroseeds presidents ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 2000\u20132003 || Anthony Keeling, Elsoms Seeds Ltd. (UK)\n|-\n| 2003\u20132006 || Sten Moberg, [[Lantm\u00e4nnen|Sval\u00f6f Weibull]] (Sweden)\n|-\n| 2006\u20132009 