{"title_page": "La Malinche", "text_new": "{{short description|Nahua aide to Hernan Cortez}}\n{{For|the volcano in Tlaxcala|Malinche (volcano)}}\n\n'''Marina''' {{IPA-es|ma\u02c8\u027eina|}} or '''Malintzin''' {{IPA-nah|ma\u02c8lintsin|}} (c. 1500 \u2013 c. 1529), more popularly known as '''La Malinche''' {{IPA-es|la ma\u02c8lint\u0283e|}}, was a [[Nahua peoples|Nahua]] woman from the Mexican Gulf Coast, who played a key role in the [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire]], acting as an interpreter, advisor, and intermediary for the Spanish conquistador, [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]]. She was one of 20 women slaves given to the Spaniards by the natives of [[Tabasco]] in 1519.{{sfn|Thomas|1993|p=171\u2013172}} Later, she gave birth to Cort\u00e9s's first son, [[Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s (son of Malinche)|Mart\u00edn]], who is considered one of the first [[Mestizos]] (people of mixed [[European ethnic groups|European]] and [[indigenous American]] ancestry).\n\nThe historical figure of Marina has been intermixed with Aztec legends (such as that of [[La Llorona]], a ghost woman who weeps for her lost children).{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=7}} Her reputation has been altered over the years according to changing social and political perspectives, especially after the Mexican Revolution, when she was portrayed in dramas, novels, and paintings as an evil or scheming temptress.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=12-13}} In Mexico today, La Malinche remains iconically potent. She is understood in various and often conflicting aspects as the embodiment of treachery, the quintessential victim, or simply as symbolic mother of the new Mexican people.\n\nThe term ''[[malinchista]]'' refers to a disloyal compatriot, especially in Mexico.\n\nBecause of her controversial signification, a statue of La Malinche, Cort\u00e9s, and their son Mart\u00edn was removed soon after it was erected in Coyoacan, in the outskirts of Mexico City, in 1982. The statue was intended to be respectful of her trials and to emphasize the mestizo (or mixed-blood) character of the nation. However, student protests erupted: the protesters wanted no monument that presented La Malinche in a positive light, for in their minds she was too closely associated with domination by outsiders and with betrayal.<ref>[[Camilla Townsend]] (2006). ''Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico''. New Mexico: [[University of New Mexico Press]]. p.4</ref>\n\n==Name==\nMalinche is known by many names.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=2}}{{sfn|Herrera-Sobek|2005|pp=112\u2013113}} She was [[Baptism|baptized]] as Marina,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=292}} and was referred to as such by the Spaniards, often preceded with [[honorific]] {{lang|es|[[Don (honorific)|do\u00f1a]]}}.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=27}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=42, 180\u2013182}} The Nahuas called her 'Malintzin', derived from 'Malina' (a [[Nahuatl]] rendering of her Spanish name) and the honorific suffix {{lang|nah|-tzin}}.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=55}} According to the historian [[Camilla Townsend]], the [[Vocative case|vocative]] suffix {{lang|nah|-e}} is sometimes added at the end of the name, giving the form ''Malintzine'', which would be shortened to 'Malintze', and heard by the Spanish as 'Malinche'.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=55}}{{efn|The vocative form is used when addressing someone, so \"Malintzine\" and \"Malintze\" are more or less equivalent to \"O Marina\". Although the shortened form \u201cMalintze\u201d is unusual, it appears repeatedly in the ''[[Anales de Tlatelolco|Annals of Tlatelolco]]'', alongside \u201cMalintzine\u201d.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=242}}}} Another possibility is that the Spaniards simply did not hear the 'whispered' {{lang|nah|-n}} of the name ''Malintzin''.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}}\n\nHer name at birth is unknown.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=xiii}} It has been popularly assumed since at least the 19th century{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} that she was originally named 'Malinalli'{{efn|Also Malinal,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} Ce-Malinalli,{{sfn|Herrera-Sobek|2005|pp=112\u2013113}}{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}} and so forth.}} (Nahuatl for 'grass'), after the [[Aztec calendar#Day signs|day sign]] on which she was supposedly born,{{sfn|Downs|2008|p=398}} and that Marina was chosen as her [[Christian name]] on account of [[Phonetics|phonetic]] similarity,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} but modern historians have rejected these propositions.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} The Nahuas associate the day sign 'Malinalli' with bad or even 'evil' connotations,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Downs|2008|p=398}}{{sfn|Cypess|1991|pp=60\u201361}} and they are known to avoid using such day signs as personal names.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=191}} Moreover, there would be little reason for the Spaniards to ask the natives what their personal names were before christening them with similar-sounding [[Spanish name]]s.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=6}}\n\nAnother title that is often assumed to be part of her original name is \u201cTenepal\u201d. This, according to the linguist and historian [[Frances Karttunen]], originated as an annotation made by the Nahua historian [[Chimalpahin]] on his copy of G\u00f3mara's biography of Cort\u00e9s, which says that Marina was also known as \"Malintzin Tenepal\".{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} Tenepal is probably derived from the Nahuatl [[Root (linguistics)|root]] {{lang|nah|tene}} which means \u201clip-possessor, one who speaks vigorously\u201d{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}} or \u201cone who has a facility with words\u201d,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=181}} and [[postposition]] {{lang|nah|-pal}}, which means \u201cby means of\u201d.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}} Thus, Malintzin Tenepal is most likely intended to be a direct translation of Spanish {{lang|es|do\u00f1a Marina la lengua}},{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}} with {{lang|es|la lengua}} (\"the interpreter\", literally \"the tongue\"{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=4}}) being her Spanish [[sobriquet]].{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}}\n\n== Life ==\n=== Background ===\n[[File:Codex azcatitlan222.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|right|[[Codex Azcatitlan]], [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]] and Malinche (far right), early 16th-century indigenous pictorial manuscript of the conquest of Mexico]]\nMalinche's birthdate is unknown,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} but it is estimated to be around 1500, and likely no later than 1505.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=11}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=1}}{{efn|{{harvtxt|Karttunen|1994|p=1}} gives \"{{abbr|ca.|circa}} 1500\" for her birth year, while {{harvtxt|Townsend|2006|p=11}} writes that she was born before [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] (who was born in February 1500) turned five.}} She was born in an {{lang|nah|[[altepetl]]}} that was either a part or a [[tributary state|tributary]] of a Mesoamerican state whose center was located on the bank of the [[Coatzacoalcos River]] to the east of the Aztec Empire.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}}{{efn|Malinche's homeland never became part of the Aztec Empire.{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=522}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}} Around the time of the conquest, the region probably consisted of \u201csmall, loosely allied city-states\u201d{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=522}} with some degree of influences from the Aztecs and various Maya states, but most are relatively autonomous and paid tribute to no one.{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=116\u2013117}}}} Records disagree about the exact name of the {{lang|nah|altepetl}} where she was born into.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} In three unrelated legal proceedings that occurred not long after her death, various witnesses who claimed to have known her personally, including her own daughter, said that she was born in [[Oluta|Olutla]]. The {{lang|es|probanza}} of her grandson also mentioned Olutla as her birthplace.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}} Her daughter also added that the {{lang|nah|altepetl}} of Olutla was related to Tetiquipaque, although the nature of this relationship is unclear.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}} In the ''[[Florentine Codex]]'', Malinche's homeland is mentioned as \"Teticpac\", which could be the singular form of Tetiquipaque.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}} G\u00f3mara writes that she came from \"Uiluta\" (presumably a variant of ''Olutla''), although he departs from other sources by writing that it was in the region of [[Jalisco]]. D\u00edaz, on the other hand, gives \"Painalla\" as her birthplace.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}}\n\nHer family is reported to be of noble background;{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} G\u00f3mara writes that her father was related to a local ruler,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=16\u201317, 233}} while D\u00edaz recounts that her parents themselves were rulers.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=5}} Townsend notes that while Olutla at the time probably had a [[Popoluca]] majority, the ruling elite, which Malinche supposedly belonged to, would have been Nahuatl-speaking.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=16\u201317, 233}} Another hint that supports her noble origin is her apparent ability to understand the courtly language of {{lang|nah|[[Nahuatl#Stylistics|tecpillahtolli]]}} (\u201clordly speech\u201d), a Nahuatl [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]] that is significantly different from the commoner's speech and has to be learned.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}} The fact that she was often referred to as a {{lang|es|do\u00f1a}}, at the time when it was not commonly used even in Spain, also indicates that she was viewed as a noblewoman,{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}} although it is also possible that the honorific was attributed to her because of her important role in the conquest.{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=xiii}}\n\nProbably between the age of 8 and 12,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22\u201324}} Malinche was either sold or kidnapped into slavery.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}} D\u00edaz famously wrote that after her father's death, she was given away to merchants by her mother and stepfather so that their own son (Malinche's stepbrother) could succeed as [[heir]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22\u201324}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} Some scholars, historians and literary critics alike, have cast doubt upon D\u00edaz's account of her origin.{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=23\u201324}}{{sfn|Franco|1999|pp=76\u201378}} Nevertheless, Townsend considers it likely that some of her people were complicit in [[Human trafficking|trafficking]] her, regardless of the reason.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22}} Malinche was taken to Xicalango,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}} a major port city in the region.{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=135\u2013136}} She was later purchased by a group of Chontal Maya who brought her to the town of Potonch\u00e1n. It was here that Malinche started to learn the [[Chontal Maya language|Chontal Maya]] language, and perhaps also [[Yucatec Maya language|Yucatec Maya]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}}{{efn|Chontal is closely related to Yucatecan, but they are sufficiently distinct to hamper [[Mutual intelligibility|intelligibility]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} Around this time, it was not uncommon to see traders from the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] (who spoke Yucatecan) in the region,{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=116\u2013117}} and Malinche may have learned the language from them.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}} Alternatively, she may have done some adjustment to be able to converse with speakers of other [[Mayan languages|Maya varieties]], which, nevertheless, was rather unusual.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}}} This would later enable her to communicate with [[Ger\u00f3nimo de Aguilar|Jer\u00f3nimo de Aguilar]], another interpreter for Cortes who also spoke Yucatec Maya, alongside his native Spanish.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}\n\n=== The conquest of Mexico ===\n{{quote box\n|width = 350px\n|align = right\n|quoted = true\n|salign = right\n|quote = Moteuc\u00e7oma was told how the Spaniards were bringing along with them a Mexica [Nahuatl-speaking] Indian woman called Marina, a citizen of the settlement of Teticpac, on the shore of the North Sea [Caribbean], who served as interpreter and said in the Mexican language everything that Captain don Hernando Cort\u00e9s told her to.\n|source = \u2014 Report from the emissaries to Moctezuma. ''[[Florentine&nbsp;Codex]]'', Book XII, Chapter IX{{sfn|Lockhart|1993|p=87}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}}\n}}\n\nEarly in [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire#Cort\u00e9s's expedition|his expedition to Mexico]], Cort\u00e9s was confronted by the Mayas at Potonch\u00e1n.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=5}} After suffering a significant loss of lives in the battle that ensued, the Mayas asked for peace, and in the following days, presented the Spaniards with gifts of food and gold, as well as twenty slave women. Malinche was one of the women presented to the Spaniards.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=61\u201363}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=35\u201336}} She and the other women were baptized and subsequently distributed among Cort\u00e9s's men, not only as servants, but also to provide sexual services.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=35\u201336}} Malinche was given to [[Alonso Hern\u00e1ndez Puertocarrero]], one of Cort\u00e9s's captains{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} who was also a [[first cousin]] to the [[count]] of Cort\u00e9s's hometown, [[Medell\u00edn, Spain|Medell\u00edn]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=37}}\n\nMalinche's linguistic gift went undiscovered{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} until the Spaniards first encounter with the Nahuatl-speaking people at [[San Juan de Ul\u00faa]].{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} Moctezuma's emissaries had come to inspect them,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=65}} but Aguilar found himself unable to understand their words.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} When it was realized that Malinche was able to converse with the emissaries, she and Aguilar were set aside by Cort\u00e9s, who, according to G\u00f3mara, promised her \u201cmore than liberty\u201d if she would assist him in finding and communicating with Moctezuma.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} Cort\u00e9s took Malinche back from Puertocarrero,{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} who was later given another indigenous woman before he was sent back to Spain.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=53}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=7}} Through Aguilar and Malinche, Cort\u00e9s talked with Moctezuma's emissaries. The emissaries also brought artists to make paintings of Malinche, Cort\u00e9s, and the rest of the group, as well as their ships and weapons, to be sent as records for Moctezuma.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=42}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=67}} D\u00edaz later said that the Nahuas also addressed Cort\u00e9s as \"Malinche\";{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} they apparently took her as a point of reference for the group.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=56, 242}}{{efn|D\u00edaz explained this phenomenon by positing that \u201cMalinche\u201d in reference to Cort\u00e9s as a shorthand for \u201cMarina's Captain\u201d, because she was always in his company.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=293\u2013294}} However, according to Townsend, [[possessive]] construction in Nahuatl cannot be shortened that way. Moreover, D\u00edaz's theory cannot explain the usage of the name \u201cMalinche\u201d to refer to another Spaniard by the name of Juan Perez de Arteaga,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=56, 242}} who was learning Nahuatl from her.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=22}}}}\n\nFrom then on, Malinche would work together with Aguilar to bridge communication between the Spaniards and the Nahuas;{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=42}} Cort\u00e9s would speak Spanish with Aguilar, who then translated into Yucatec Maya for Malinche, who in turn translated into Nahuatl, before reversing the process.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=84\u201385}} The translation chain grew even longer when, after the emissaries left, they met the [[Totonac]]s,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=68, 70\u201371}} whose language was unintelligible to both Malinche and Aguilar. There, Malinche asked for Nahuatl interpreters.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=43}} Karttunen remarks that \"it is a wonder any communication was accomplished at all\", for Cort\u00e9s's Spanish words had to be translated into Maya, Nahuatl, and [[Totonac languages|Totonac]] before reaching the locals, whose answers then went back through the same chain.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}} From the meeting with the Totonacs, Cort\u00e9s learned of those who were hostile to Moctezuma.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=43}} According to the anthropologist and historian [[Ross Hassig]], this meeting was also a major turning point that \"set Cort\u00e9s's course irrevocably towards conquest\".{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=68, 70\u201371}} After securing an alliance with the Totonacs and founding the town of Villa Rica de la Vera Cruz, they started the march towards Tenochtitlan.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=73\u201374, 77}}\n\nThe first major polity that they encounter on the way to Tenochtitlan was [[Tlaxcala (Nahua state)|Tlaxcala]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=59}} Although the [[Tlaxcaltecs|Tlaxcalans]] were initially hostile to the Spaniards and their allies,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=79}} they later permitted the Spaniards to enter the city.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=62\u201363}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=86\u201389}} The Tlaxcalans negotiated an alliance with the Spaniards through Malinche and Aguilar. Later Tlaxcalan records of this meeting feature scenes where Malinche appears prominent, bridging the communication between the two sides as the Tlaxcalans presented the Spaniards with gifts of food and noblewomen to cement the alliance.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=69\u201372}} After several days in Tlaxcala, Cort\u00e9s continued the journey to Tenochtitlan by the way of [[Cholula (Mesoamerican site)|Cholula]], accompanied by a large number of Tlaxcalan soldiers.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=93}}\n\nThe Spaniards were received at Cholula and housed for several days, until, as the Spaniards claimed, the Cholulans stopped giving them food, dug secret pits, built a barricade around the city, and hid a large Aztec army in the outskirt in preparation for an attack against the Spaniards.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}} Somehow, the Spaniards learned of this plot, and, in a [[preemptive strike]], assembled and [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire#Massacre of Cholula|massacred the Cholulans]].{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}} Later accounts specifically claimed that the plot was uncovered by Malinche. According to the version provided by D\u00edaz, she was approached by a Cholulan noblewoman who promised her a marriage to the woman's son if she were to switch side. Malinche, pretending to go along with the suggestion, learned from the woman about the plot, and reported all the details to Cort\u00e9s.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=10}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}} This story has often been cited as an example of Malinche's \u201cbetrayal\u201d to her people.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}} However, the veracity of the story has been questioned by modern historians such as Hassig and Townsend.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=81\u201382}} It has been suggested that the Tlaxcalans were the real mastermind behind the massacre. Cholula had previously supported Tlaxcala before joining the Aztec Empire one or two years prior, and losing them as an ally was a hard hit for the Tlaxcalans, whose state was now completely encircled by the Aztecs.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=81\u201382}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=210}} It is possible that the attack on the Cholulans was in fact a test from the Tlaxcalans for the Spaniards' trustworthiness.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=210}} In this view, thus, Malinche's \u201cheroic\u201d discovery of the purported plot is only a part of the justification for the massacre.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}}\n\n[[File:Cortez & La Malinche.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.5|The meeting of Cort\u00e9s and Moctezuma II, with Malinche acting as interpreter.]]\nThe combined forces reached Tenochtitlan in early November 1519, and was met by Moctezuma in a causeway leading to the city.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=77}} Malinche was in the middle of this event, translating the conversation between Cort\u00e9s and Moctezuma.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}} Gomara writes that Moctezuma was \"speaking through Malinche and Aguilar\", although other records indicate that Malinche was already translating directly,{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}} as she had quickly learned some Spanish herself.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2019|pp=99, 243}} Moctezuma's flowery speech delivered through Malinche at the meeting has been claimed by the Spaniards to represent a submission, but this interpretation is not followed by modern historians.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}} The deferential nature of the speech can be explained by Moctezuma's usage of {{lang|nah|tecpillahtolli}}, a Nahuatl register known for its indirection and complex set of reverential affixes.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=11}} Despite Malinche's apparent ability to understand {{lang|nah|tecpillahtolli}}, it is possible that some nuances were lost in translation,{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}} and the Spanish, deliberately or not, may have misinterpreted Moctezuma's actual words.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}}\n\nFollowing the fall of Tenochtitl\u00e1n in late 1521 and the birth of her son [[Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s (son of do\u00f1a Marina)|Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s]] in 1522, Marina stayed in a house Cort\u00e9s built for her in the town of Coyoac\u00e1n, eight miles south of Tenochtitl\u00e1n, the Aztec capital city, while it was being rebuilt as Mexico City. Cort\u00e9s took Marina to quell a rebellion in [[Honduras]] in 1524\u20131526 when she is seen serving again as interpreter (suggestive of a knowledge of Maya dialects beyond Chontal and Yucat\u00e1n.) While in the mountain town of Orizaba in central Mexico, she married [[Juan Jaramillo]], a Spanish [[Hidalgo (Spanish nobility)|hidalgo]].<ref>Gordon, Helen. ''Voice of the Vanquished: The Story of the Slave Marina and Hernan Cort\u00e9s''. Chicago: University Editions, 1995, page 454.</ref> Some contemporary scholars have estimated that she died less than a decade after the conquest of Mexico-Tenochtitlan at some point before February 1529.<ref>Chaison, Joanne. \"Mysterious Malinche: A Case of Mistaken Identity,\" ''The Americas'' 32, N. 4 (1976).</ref>{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=263}} She was survived by her son Don Mart\u00edn, who would be raised primarily by his father's family, and a daughter Do\u00f1a Mar\u00eda, who would be raised by Jaramillo and his second wife Do\u00f1a Beatriz de Andrada.<ref>Camilla Townsend, ''Malintzin's Choices: An Indian Woman in the Conquest of Mexico.'' University of New Mexico Press, 2006, pp. 168\u2013187.</ref>\n\n=== Role of La Malinche in the conquest of Mexico ===\n[[File:Malinche Tlaxcala.jpg|thumb|right|La Malinche and Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s in the city of Xaltelolco, in a drawing from the late 16th-century [[Aztec codices|codex]] ''[[History of Tlaxcala]]'']]\nFor the [[conquistador]]es, having a reliable interpreter was important enough, but there is evidence that Marina's role and influence were larger still. [[Bernal D\u00edaz del Castillo]], a soldier who, as an old man, produced the most comprehensive of the eye-witness accounts, the ''[[Historia verdadera de la conquista de la Nueva Espa\u00f1a]]'' (\"True Story of the Conquest of New Spain\"), speaks repeatedly and reverentially of the \"great lady\" Do\u00f1a Marina (always using the honorific title Do\u00f1a). \"Without the help of Do\u00f1a Marina\", he writes, \"we would not have understood the language of New Spain and Mexico.\" [[Rodr\u00edguez de Oca\u00f1a]], another conquistador, relates Cort\u00e9s' assertion that after God, Marina was the main reason for his success.\n\nThe evidence from indigenous sources is even more interesting, both in the commentaries about her role, and in her prominence in the codex drawings made of conquest events. Although to some Marina may be known as a traitor, she was not viewed as such by all the Tlaxcalan. In some depictions they portrayed her as \"larger than life\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |title=Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico |last=Townsend |first=Camilla |publisher=University of New Mexico Press |location=New Mexico |year=2006 |pages=74\u201376 |isbn=0-8263-3405-9}}</ref> sometimes larger than Cort\u00e9s, in rich clothing, and an alliance is shown between her and the Tlaxcalan instead of them and the Spaniards. They respected and trusted her and portrayed her in this light generations after the Spanish conquest.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the ''[[History of Tlaxcala|Lienzo de Tlaxcala (History of Tlaxcala)]]'', for example, not only is Cort\u00e9s rarely portrayed without Marina poised by his side, but she is shown at times on her own, seemingly directing events as an independent authority. If she had been trained for court life, as in D\u00edaz's account, her relationship to Cort\u00e9s may have followed the familiar pattern of marriage among native elite classes. The role of the Nahua wife acquired through an alliance would have been to assist her husband achieve his military and diplomatic objectives.<ref>Restall, Matthew. Seven Myths of the Spanish Conquest</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mesolore.org/viewer/view/2/Lienzo-de-Tlaxcala |title=Mesolore: A research & teaching tool on Mesoamerica |website=www.mesolore.org}}</ref>\n\nToday's historians give great credit to Marina's diplomatic skills, with some \"almost tempted to think of her as the real conqueror of Mexico.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Brandon |first=William |title=The Rise and Fall of North American Indians |year=2003 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart Publishers |location=Lanham, MD |page=88 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lde5K93ozuMC&pg=PA88&lpg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In fact, old conquistadors on various occasions would remember that one of her greatest skills had been her ability to convince other Indians of what she herself could see clearly, which was that it was useless in the long run to stand against Spanish metal and Spanish ships. In contrast with earlier parts of D\u00edaz del Castillo's account, after Marina's diplomacy began assisting Cort\u00e9s, the Spanish were forced into combat on one more occasion.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brandon |first=William |title=The Rise and Fall of North American Indians |year=2003 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart Publishers |location=Lanham, MD |page=88 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lde5K93ozuMC&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nHad La Malinche not been part of the Conquest of Mexico for her linguistic gift, communication between the Spanish and the Indigenous would have been much harder. La Malinche knew to speak in different registers and tones between certain Indigenous tribes and people. For the Nahua audiences, she spoke rhetorically, formally, and high-handedly. This shift into formality gave the Nahua the impression that she was a noblewoman who knew what she was talking about.<ref>Townsend, Camilla (2006). Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico. New Mexico: University of New Mexico Press. pp.58</ref>\n\n== Malinche\u2019s image in contemporary Mexico ==\n[[File:Monumento al Mestizaje.jpg|thumb|Modern statue of Cort\u00e9s, Marina, and their son Mart\u00edn, which was moved from a prominent place of display to an obscure one, due to protests]]\n\nMalinche's image has become a mythical [[archetype]] that [[Hispanic America]]n artists have represented in various forms of art. Her figure permeates historical, cultural, and social dimensions of Hispanic American cultures.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=Intro.}} In modern times and in several genres, she is compared with the [[La Llorona]] (folklore story of the woman weeping for lost children), and the Mexican [[soldaderas]] (women who fought beside men during the [[Mexican Revolution]])<ref>Salas{{Page needed|date=October 2010}}</ref> for their brave actions.\n\nLa Malinche's legacy is one of myth mixed with legend, and the opposing opinions of the Mexican people about the legendary woman. Some see her as a founding figure of the Mexican nation, while others continue to see her as a traitor\u2014as may be assumed from a legend that she had a twin sister who went North, and from the pejorative [[nickname]] ''[[La Chingada]]'' associated with her twin.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nFeminist interventions into the figure of Malinche began in 1960s. The work of [[Rosario Castellanos]] was particularly significant; Chicanas began to refer to her as a \"mother\" as they adopted her as symbolism for duality and complex identity.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Castellanos |first=Rosario |title=Otra vez Sor Juana\" (\"Once Again Sor Juana\") |date=1963}}</ref> Castellanos's subsequent poem \"La Mallinche\" recast her not as a traitor but as a victim.<ref name=\"Romero2005\">{{cite book |author=Rolando Romero |title=Feminism, Nation and Myth: La Malinche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dfesWiXwkdQC&pg=PA28 |date=2005-01-01 |publisher=Arte Publico Press |isbn=978-1-61192-042-0 |pages=28\u2013 }}</ref> Mexican feminists defended Malinche as a woman caught between cultures, forced to make complex decisions, who ultimately served as a mother of a new race.<ref name=\"CoerverPasztor2004\">{{cite book |author1=Don M. Coerver |author2=Suzanne B. Pasztor |author3=Robert Buffington |title=Mexico: An Encyclopedia of Contemporary Culture and History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSred4NyOKoC&pg=PA200 |year=2004 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-57607-132-8 |pages=200\u2013 }}</ref>\n\nToday in Mexican Spanish, the words ''[[malinchism]]o''  and ''malinchista'' are used to denounce Mexicans who are perceived as denying their own cultural heritage by preferring foreign cultural expressions.<ref>Fortes De Leff, J. (2002). Racism in Mexico: Cultural Roots and Clinical Interventions1. Family Process, 41(4), 619-623.</ref>\n\nSome historians believe that La Malinche saved her people from the Aztecs, who held a hegemony throughout the territory and demanded tribute from its inhabitants.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Some Mexicans also credit her with having brought Christianity to the New World from Europe, and for having influenced Cort\u00e9s to be more humane than he would otherwise have been. It is argued, however, that without her help, Cort\u00e9s would not have been successful in conquering the Aztecs as quickly, giving the Aztec people enough time to adapt to new technology and methods of warfare. From that viewpoint, she is seen as one who betrayed the indigenous people by siding with the Spaniards. Recently a number of feminist Latinas have decried such a categorization as [[scapegoating]].{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=12}}\n\nPresident [[Jos\u00e9 L\u00f3pez Portillo]] commissioned a sculpture of Cort\u00e9s, Do\u00f1a Marina, and their son Mart\u00edn, which was placed in front of Cort\u00e9s's house in the [[Coyoacan]] section of Mexico City.  Once L\u00f3pez Portillo left office, the sculpture was removed to an obscure park in the capital.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-03-31-wr-223-story.html/ It is time to stop vilifying the \"Spanish father of Mexico\"], accessed 10 June 2019</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:La Malinche statue.jpg|right|thumb|La Malinche, as part of the ''Monumento al Mestizaje'' in Mexico City]]\n\n*A reference to La Malinche as Marina is made in the novel ''[[The Manuscript Found in Saragossa]]'' by the Polish author [[Jan Potocki]], in which she is cursed for yielding her \"heart and her country to the hateful Cortez, chief of the sea-brigands.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Potocki |first=Jan |title=The Manuscript Found at Saragossa |year=1995 |publisher=Penguin Books |author2=trans. Ian Maclean}}</ref>\n*La Malinche appears in the adventure novel ''[[Montezuma's Daughter]]'' (1893) by [[Henry Rider Haggard|H. Rider Haggard]].\n*Do\u00f1a Marina appears in the Henry King film adventure ''[[Captain from Castile (novel)|Captain from Castile]]'' (1947) played Estela Inda.\n*La Malinche is portrayed as a Christian and protector of her fellow native Mexicans in the novel ''Tlaloc Weeps for Mexico'' (1939) by [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Passuth]], and is the main protagonist in such works as the novels ''The Golden Princess'' (1954) by [[Alexander Baron]] and ''Feathered Serpent: A Novel of the Mexican Conquest'' (2002) by [[Colin Falconer (writer)|Colin Falconer]]. In contrast, she is portrayed as a duplicitous traitor in [[Gary Jennings]]' novel ''[[Aztec (novel)|Aztec]]'' (1980). A novel published in 2006 by [[Laura Esquivel]] portrays the main character as a pawn of history who becomes ''Malinche''.\n*In 1949, choreographer Jos\u00e9 Lim\u00f3n premiered the dance trio \"La Milanche\" to music by Norman Lloyd. It was the first work created by Lim\u00f3n for his own company, and was based on his memories as a child of Mexican fiestas.<ref>[http://limon.org/dances/ \"Repertory\"] ''Lim\u00f3n''</ref>\n*The story of La Malinche is told in ''Cortez and Marina'' (1963) by [[Edison Marshall]].\n*In the 1973 Mexican film ''Leyendas macabras de la colonia'', La Malinche's mummy is in the possession of Luisa, her daughter by Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s, while her spirit inhabits a cursed painting.\n*La Malinche is referred to in the songs \"[[Cortez the Killer]]\" from the 1975 album ''[[Zuma (album)|Zuma]]'' by [[Neil Young]], and \"La Malinche\" by the French band [[Feu! Chatterton]] from their 2015 album ''Ici le jour (a tout enseveli)''\n*In the animated television series ''[[The Mysterious Cities of Gold]]'' (1982), which chronicles the adventures of a Spanish boy and his companions traveling throughout South America in 1532 to seek the lost city of [[El Dorado]], a woman called Marinche becomes a dangerous adversary. The series was originally produced in Japan, and then translated into English.\n*In the fictional ''[[Star Trek]]'' universe, a starship, the USS ''Malinche'', was named for La Malinche, and appeared in the 1997 \"[[For the Uniform]]\" episode of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''. This was done by [[Hans Beimler (screenwriter)|Hans Beimler]], a native of [[Mexico City]], who together with friend [[Robert Hewitt Wolfe]] later wrote a screenplay based on La Malinche called ''The Serpent and the Eagle''.\n*La Malinche is a key character in the opera ''[[La Conquista (opera)|La Conquista]]'' (2005) by Italian composer [[Lorenzo Ferrero]].\n*Malinalli is the main character in a 2011 historical novel by Helen Heightsman Gordon, ''Malinalli of the Fifth Sun: The Slave Girl Who Changed the Fate of Mexico and Spain''.\n*Author [[Octavio Paz]] addresses the issue of La Malinche's role as the mother of Mexican culture in ''[[The Labyrinth of Solitude]]''. He uses her relation to Cort\u00e9s symbolically to represent Mexican culture as originating from rape and violation.\n*Malinal is a character in [[Graham Hancock]]'s series of novels ''War God: Nights of the Witch'' (2013) and ''War God: Return of the Plumed Serpent'' (2014), which is a fictional story describing the events related to the Hernan Cort\u00e9s' expedition to Mexico and the Spanish conquest of the Aztec empire.\n*Malinche is a character in Edward Rickford's ''The Serpent and the Eagle'', referred to variously as ''Dona Marina'' and ''Malintze''. The depiction of her character was praised by historical novelists and bloggers.\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Mexico|Biography}}\n*[[Felipillo]]\n*[[History of Mexico]]\n*[[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire]]\n*[[Women in Mexico]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n: {{cite book |last=Chapman |first=Anne M. |author-link=Anne Chapman |editor1=Karl Polanyi |editor2=Conrad M. Arensberg |editor3=Harry W. Pearson |year=1957 |chapter=Port of Trade Enclaves in Aztec and Maya Civilizations |title=Trade and Market in the Early Empires: Economies in History and Theory |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Cypess |first=Sandra Messinger |year=1991 |title=La Malinche in Mexican Literature: From History to Myth |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin, TX |isbn=9780292751347 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Downs |first=Kristina |year=2008 |title=Mirrored Archetypes: The Contrasting Cultural Roles of La Malinche and Pocahontas |journal=[[Western Folklore]] |volume=67 |issue=4 |pages=397\u2013414 |publisher=Western States Folklore Society |jstor=25474939 |location=Long Beach, CA |issn=0043-373X |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Evans |first=Susan Toby |year=2004 |title=Ancient Mexico & Central America: Archaeology and Culture History |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |location=London |isbn=9780500284407 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Franco |first=Jean |author-link=Jean Franco |editor1=Mary Louise Pratt |editor2=Kathleen Newman |year=1999 |chapter=La Malinche: from gift to sexual contract |title=Critical Passions: Selected Essays |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |location=Durham, NC |isbn=9780822322481 |pp=66\u201382 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Hassig |first=Ross |author-link=Ross Hassig |year=2006 |title=Mexico and the Spanish Conquest |publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]] |location=Norman, OK |isbn=9780806182087 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Herrera-Sobek |first=Mar\u00eda |editor1=Rolando J. Romero |editor2=Amanda Nolacea Harris |year=2005 |chapter=In Search of La Malinche: Pictorial Representations of a Mytho-Historical Figure |title=Feminism, Nation and Myth: La Malinche |publisher=Arte P\u00fablico Press |location=Houston, TX |isbn=9781611920420 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Karttunen |first=Frances |author-link=Frances Karttunen |year=1994 |title=Between Worlds: Interpreters, Guides, and Survivors |publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]] |location=New Brunswick, NJ |isbn=9780813520315 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Karttunen |first=Frances |author-mask=3 |year=1997 |chapter=Rethinking Malinche |title=Indian Women: Gender Differences and Identity in Early Mexico |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=Norman, OK |isbn=9780806129600 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite encyclopedia |last=Karttunen |first=Frances |author-mask=3 |year=2001 |orig-year=1997 |chapter=Malinche and ''Malinchismo'' |title=Concise Encyclopedia of Mexico |pages=352\u2013355 |publisher=[[Fitzroy Dearborn]] |location=Chicago |isbn=9781579583378 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Lockhart |editor-first=James |editor-link=James Lockhart (historian) |translator=James Lockhart |translator-link=James Lockhart (historian) |year=1993 |title=We People Here: Nahuatl Accounts of the Conquest of Mexico |series=Repertorium Columbianum |volume=1 |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |location=Berkeley, CA |isbn=9780520078758 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Restall |first=Matthew |author-link=Matthew Restall |year=2003 |title=Seven Myths of the Spanish Conquest |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford and New York |isbn=9780195176117 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Restall |first=Matthew |author-mask=3 |year=2018 |title=When Montezuma Met Cort\u00e9s: The True Story of the Meeting that Changed History |publisher=[[Ecco Press|Ecco]] |location=New York |isbn=9780062427267 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Townsend |first=Camilla |author-link=Camilla Townsend |year=2006 |title=Malintzin's Choices: An Indian Woman in the Conquest of Mexico |publisher=[[University of New Mexico Press]] |location=Albuquerque |isbn=9780826334053 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Townsend |first=Camilla |author-mask=3 |year=2019 |title=Fifth Sun: A New History of the Aztecs |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780190673062 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Valde\u00f3n |first=Roberto A. |year=2013 |title=Do\u00f1a Marina/La Malinche: A Historiographical Approach to the Interpreter/Traitor |journal=[[Target (journal)|Target: International Journal of Translation Studies]] |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=157\u2013179 |publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]] |location=Amsterdam |doi=10.1075/target.25.2.02val |issn=0924-1884 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Agogino |first=George A. |first2=Dominique E. |last2=Stevens |first3=Lynda |last3=Carlotta |title=Dona Marina and the legend of La Llorona |journal=Anthropological Journal of Canada |volume=2 |issue=1 |date=1973 |pages=27\u201329}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Calafell |first=Bernadette M. |title=Pro(re)claiming Loss: a Performance Pilgrimage in Search of Malintzin Tenepal |journal=Text and Performance Quarterly |volume=25 |issue=1 |date=2005 |pages=43\u201356}} \n* {{cite book |last=Del Rio |first=Fanny |title=La verdadera historia de Malinche |publisher=Grijalbo |location=M\u00e9xico, D.F. |date=2009 |isbn=978-607-429-593-1}}\n* {{cite book |last=D\u00edaz del Castillo |first=Bernal |date=1963 |orig-year=1632 |title=The Conquest of New Spain |translator=J.M. Cohen |publisher=The Folio Society |location=London}}\n* {{cite book |last=Fuentes |first=Patricia de |title=The Conquistadors: First Person Accounts of the Conquest of Mexico |url=https://archive.org/details/conquistadorsfir00fuen |url-access=registration |publisher=Orion |location=New York |date=1963}}\n* {{cite book |last=Maura |first=Juan Francisco |title=Women in the Conquest of the Americas |translator=John F. Deredita |publisher=Peter Lang |location=New York |date=1997}}\n* {{cite book |last=Paz |first=Octavio |title=The Labyrinth of Solitude |url=https://archive.org/details/lish00octa |url-access=registration |publisher=Grove Press |location=New York |date=1961}}\n* {{cite book |last=Somonte |first=Mariano G. |title=Do\u00f1a Marina: \"La Malinche\" |publisher=Edimex |location=Mexico City |date=1971}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Hugh |author-link=Hugh Thomas (historian) |title=Conquest: Montezuma, Cort\u00e9s, and the Fall of Old Mexico |url=https://archive.org/details/conquestmontezum00thom |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |year=1993 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Vivancos P\u00e9rez |first=Ricardo F. |chapter=Malinche |title=Celebrating Latino Folklore: An Encyclopedia of Cultural Traditions. Vol. II |editor=Mar\u00eda Herrera-Sobek |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara, CA |date=2012 |pages=750\u2013759}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Henderson |first1=James D. |title=Ten notable women of Latin America |url=https://archive.org/details/tennotablewomeno00hend |url-access=registration |date=1978 |publisher=Nelson Hall |location=Chicago}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|La Malinche}}\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/26/world/after-500-years-Cort\u00e9s-s-girlfriend-is-not-forgiven.html/ \"Cort\u00e9s girlfriend is not forgiven\". The New York Times. accessed 10 June 2019]\n*[http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/Cort\u00e9s/4.html#Malinche/Do\u00d2aMarina Hernando Cort\u00e9s on the Web : Malinche / Do\u00f1a Marina] (resources)\n*[http://chapala.com/chapala/ojo2007/defensemalinche.html in defense of Malinche]\n*[http://www.mexicolore.co.uk/aztecs/spanish-conquest/dona-marina-part-1 Making Herself Indispensable, Condemned for Surviving: Do\u00f1a Marina (Part 1)]\n*[http://www.mexicolore.co.uk/aztecs/spanish-conquest/dona-marina-part-2 Making Herself Indispensable, Condemned for Surviving: Do\u00f1a Marina (Part 2)]\n*[http://www.teck-translations.com/la-malinche-an-ambivalent-interpreter-from-the-past/ La Malinche, an ambivalent interpreter from the past]\n*[http://www.ucm.es/info/especulo/numero23/malinche.html Leyenda y nacionalismo: alegor\u00edas de la derrota en La Malinche y Florinda \"La Cava\"], Spanish-language article by Juan F. Maura comparing La Cava and Mexican Malinche.{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinche, La}}\n[[Category:1490s births]]\n[[Category:1500s births]]\n[[Category:1520s deaths]]\n[[Category:1550s deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century indigenous people of the Americas]]\n[[Category:16th-century Mexican people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Mexican women]]\n[[Category:History of the Aztecs]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Mexicans]]\n[[Category:Interpreters]]\n[[Category:Mexican folklore]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Native American women in warfare]]\n[[Category:Mexican slaves]]\n[[Category:Women in 16th-century warfare]]\n[[Category:Women in the Conquest of Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nahua aide to Hernan Cortez}}\n{{For|the volcano in Tlaxcala|Malinche (volcano)}}\n\n'''Marina''' {{IPA-es|ma\u02c8\u027eina|}} or '''Malintzin''' {{IPA-nah|ma\u02c8lintsin|}} (c. 1500 \u2013 c. 1529), more popularly known as '''La Malinche''' {{IPA-es|la ma\u02c8lint\u0283e|}}, was a [[Nahua peoples|Nahua]] woman from the Mexican Gulf Coast, who played a key role in the [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire]], acting as an interpreter, advisor, and intermediary for the Spanish conquistador, [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]]. She was one of 20 women slaves given to the Spaniards by the natives of [[Tabasco]] in 1519.{{sfn|Thomas|1993|p=171\u2013172}} Later, she gave birth to Cort\u00e9s's first son, [[Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s (son of Malinche)|Mart\u00edn]], who is considered one of the first [[Mestizos]] (people of mixed [[European ethnic groups|European]] and [[indigenous American]] ancestry).\n\nThe historical figure of Marina has been intermixed with Aztec legends (such as that of [[La Llorona]], a ghost woman who weeps for her lost children).{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=7}} Her reputation has been altered over the years according to changing social and political perspectives, especially after the Mexican Revolution, when she was portrayed in dramas, novels, and paintings as an evil or scheming temptress.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=12-13}} In Mexico today, La Malinche remains iconically potent. She is understood in various and often conflicting aspects as the embodiment of treachery, the quintessential victim, or simply as symbolic mother of the new Mexican people.\n\nThe term ''[[malinchista]]'' refers to a disloyal compatriot, especially in Mexico.\n\nBecause of her controversial signification, a statue of La Malinche, Cort\u00e9s, and their son Mart\u00edn was removed soon after it was erected in Coyoacan, in the outskirts of Mexico City, in 1982. The statue was intended to be respectful of her trials and to emphasize the mestizo (or mixed-blood) character of the nation. However, student protests erupted: the protesters wanted no monument that presented La Malinche in a positive light, for in their minds she was too closely associated with domination by outsiders and with betrayal.<ref>[[Camilla Townsend]] (2006). ''Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico''. New Mexico: [[University of New Mexico Press]]. p.4</ref>\n\n==Name==\nMalinche is known by many names.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=2}}{{sfn|Herrera-Sobek|2005|pp=112\u2013113}} She was [[Baptism|baptized]] as Marina,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=292}} and was referred to as such by the Spaniards, often preceded with [[honorific]] {{lang|es|[[Don (honorific)|do\u00f1a]]}}.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=27}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=42, 180\u2013182}} The Nahuas called her 'Malintzin', derived from 'Malina' (a [[Nahuatl]] rendering of her Spanish name) and the honorific suffix {{lang|nah|-tzin}}.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=55}} According to the historian [[Camilla Townsend]], the [[Vocative case|vocative]] suffix {{lang|nah|-e}} is sometimes added at the end of the name, giving the form ''Malintzine'', which would be shortened to 'Malintze', and heard by the Spanish as 'Malinche'.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=55}}{{efn|The vocative form is used when addressing someone, so \"Malintzine\" and \"Malintze\" are more or less equivalent to \"O Marina\". Although the shortened form \u201cMalintze\u201d is unusual, it appears repeatedly in the ''[[Anales de Tlatelolco|Annals of Tlatelolco]]'', alongside \u201cMalintzine\u201d.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=242}}}} Another possibility is that the Spaniards simply did not hear the 'whispered' {{lang|nah|-n}} of the name ''Malintzin''.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}}\n\nHer name at birth is unknown.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=xiii}} It has been popularly assumed since at least the 19th century{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} that she was originally named 'Malinalli'{{efn|Also Malinal,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} Ce-Malinalli,{{sfn|Herrera-Sobek|2005|pp=112\u2013113}}{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}} and so forth.}} (Nahuatl for 'grass'), after the [[Aztec calendar#Day signs|day sign]] on which she was supposedly born,{{sfn|Downs|2008|p=398}} and that Marina was chosen as her [[Christian name]] on account of [[Phonetics|phonetic]] similarity,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} but modern historians have rejected these propositions.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} The Nahuas associate the day sign 'Malinalli' with bad or even 'evil' connotations,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Downs|2008|p=398}}{{sfn|Cypess|1991|pp=60\u201361}} and they are known to avoid using such day signs as personal names.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=12}}{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=191}} Moreover, there would be little reason for the Spaniards to ask the natives what their personal names were before christening them with similar-sounding [[Spanish name]]s.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=6}}\n\nAnother title that is often assumed to be part of her original name is \u201cTenepal\u201d. This, according to the linguist and historian [[Frances Karttunen]], originated as an annotation made by the Nahua historian [[Chimalpahin]] on his copy of G\u00f3mara's biography of Cort\u00e9s, which says that Marina was also known as \"Malintzin Tenepal\".{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}} Tenepal is probably derived from the Nahuatl [[Root (linguistics)|root]] {{lang|nah|tene}} which means \u201clip-possessor, one who speaks vigorously\u201d{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}} or \u201cone who has a facility with words\u201d,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=181}} and [[postposition]] {{lang|nah|-pal}}, which means \u201cby means of\u201d.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=352}} Thus, Malintzin Tenepal is most likely intended to be a direct translation of Spanish {{lang|es|do\u00f1a Marina la lengua}},{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}} with {{lang|es|la lengua}} (\"the interpreter\", literally \"the tongue\"{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=4}}) being her Spanish [[sobriquet]].{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=302}}\n\n== Life ==\n=== Background ===\n[[File:Codex azcatitlan222.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|right|[[Codex Azcatitlan]], [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]] and Malinche (far right), early 16th-century indigenous pictorial manuscript of the conquest of Mexico]]\nMalinche's birthdate is unknown,{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=33}} but it is estimated to be around 1500, and likely no later than 1505.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=11}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=1}}{{efn|{{harvtxt|Karttunen|1994|p=1}} gives \"{{abbr|ca.|circa}} 1500\" for her birth year, while {{harvtxt|Townsend|2006|p=11}} writes that she was born before [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] (who was born in February 1500) turned five.}} She was born in an {{lang|nah|[[altepetl]]}} that was either a part or a [[tributary state|tributary]] of a Mesoamerican state whose center was located on the bank of the [[Coatzacoalcos River]] to the east of the Aztec Empire.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}}{{efn|Malinche's homeland never became part of the Aztec Empire.{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=522}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}} Around the time of the conquest, the region probably consisted of \u201csmall, loosely allied city-states\u201d{{sfn|Evans|2004|p=522}} with some degree of influences from the Aztecs and various Maya states, but most are relatively autonomous and paid tribute to no one.{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=116\u2013117}}}} Records disagree about the exact name of the {{lang|nah|altepetl}} where she was born into.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} In three unrelated legal proceedings that occurred not long after her death, various witnesses who claimed to have known her personally, including her own daughter, said that she was born in [[Oluta|Olutla]]. The {{lang|es|probanza}} of her grandson also mentioned Olutla as her birthplace.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}} Her daughter also added that the {{lang|nah|altepetl}} of Olutla was related to Tetiquipaque, although the nature of this relationship is unclear.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=13\u201314}} In the ''[[Florentine Codex]]'', Malinche's homeland is mentioned as \"Teticpac\", which could be the singular form of Tetiquipaque.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}} G\u00f3mara writes that she came from \"Uiluta\" (presumably a variant of ''Olutla''), although he departs from other sources by writing that it was in the region of [[Jalisco]]. D\u00edaz, on the other hand, gives \"Painalla\" as her birthplace.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=230\u2013232}}\n\nHer family is reported to be of noble background;{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} G\u00f3mara writes that her father was related to a local ruler,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=16\u201317, 233}} while D\u00edaz recounts that her parents themselves were rulers.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=5}} Townsend notes that while Olutla at the time probably had a [[Popoluca]] majority, the ruling elite, which Malinche supposedly belonged to, would have been Nahuatl-speaking.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=16\u201317, 233}} Another hint that supports her noble origin is her apparent ability to understand the courtly language of {{lang|nah|[[Nahuatl#Stylistics|tecpillahtolli]]}} (\u201clordly speech\u201d), a Nahuatl [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]] that is significantly different from the commoner's speech and has to be learned.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}} The fact that she was often referred to as a {{lang|es|do\u00f1a}}, at the time when it was not commonly used even in Spain, also indicates that she was viewed as a noblewoman,{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}} although it is also possible that the honorific was attributed to her because of her important role in the conquest.{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=xiii}}\n\nProbably between the age of 8 and 12,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22\u201324}} Malinche was either sold or kidnapped into slavery.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}} D\u00edaz famously wrote that after her father's death, she was given away to merchants by her mother and stepfather so that their own son (Malinche's stepbrother) could succeed as [[heir]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22\u201324}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} Some scholars, historians and literary critics alike, have cast doubt upon D\u00edaz's account of her origin.{{sfn|Valde\u00f3n|2013|pp=163\u2013164}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=23\u201324}}{{sfn|Franco|1999|pp=76\u201378}} Nevertheless, Townsend considers it likely that some of her people were complicit in [[Human trafficking|trafficking]] her, regardless of the reason.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=22}} Malinche was taken to Xicalango,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}} a major port city in the region.{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=135\u2013136}} She was later purchased by a group of Chontal Maya who brought her to the town of Potonch\u00e1n. It was here that Malinche started to learn the [[Chontal Maya language|Chontal Maya]] language, and perhaps also [[Yucatec Maya language|Yucatec Maya]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}}{{efn|Chontal is closely related to Yucatecan, but they are sufficiently distinct to hamper [[Mutual intelligibility|intelligibility]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} Around this time, it was not uncommon to see traders from the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] (who spoke Yucatecan) in the region,{{sfn|Chapman|1957|pp=116\u2013117}} and Malinche may have learned the language from them.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=25\u201326}} Alternatively, she may have done some adjustment to be able to converse with speakers of other [[Mayan languages|Maya varieties]], which, nevertheless, was rather unusual.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}}} This would later enable her to communicate with [[Ger\u00f3nimo de Aguilar|Jer\u00f3nimo de Aguilar]], another interpreter for Cortes who also spoke Yucatec Maya, alongside his native Spanish.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}\n\n=== The conquest of Mexico ===\n{{quote box\n|width = 350px\n|align = right\n|quoted = true\n|salign = right\n|quote = Moteuc\u00e7oma was told how the Spaniards were bringing along with them a Mexica [Nahuatl-speaking] Indian woman called Marina, a citizen of the settlement of Teticpac, on the shore of the North Sea [Caribbean], who served as interpreter and said in the Mexican language everything that Captain don Hernando Cort\u00e9s told her to.\n|source = \u2014 Report from the emissaries to Moctezuma. ''[[Florentine&nbsp;Codex]]'', Book XII, Chapter IX{{sfn|Lockhart|1993|p=87}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}}\n}}\n\nEarly in [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire#Cort\u00e9s's expedition|his expedition to Mexico]], Cort\u00e9s was confronted by the Mayas at Potonch\u00e1n.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=5}} After suffering a significant loss of lives in the battle that ensued, the Mayas asked for peace, and in the following days, presented the Spaniards with gifts of food and gold, as well as twenty slave women. Malinche was one of the women presented to the Spaniards.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=61\u201363}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=35\u201336}} She and the other women were baptized and subsequently distributed among Cort\u00e9s's men, not only as servants, but also to provide sexual services.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=35\u201336}} Malinche was given to [[Alonso Hern\u00e1ndez Puertocarrero]], one of Cort\u00e9s's captains{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} who was also a [[first cousin]] to the [[count]] of Cort\u00e9s's hometown, [[Medell\u00edn, Spain|Medell\u00edn]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=37}}\n\nMalinche's linguistic gift went undiscovered{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}} until the Spaniards first encounter with the Nahuatl-speaking people at [[San Juan de Ul\u00faa]].{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} Moctezuma's emissaries had come to inspect them,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=65}} but Aguilar found himself unable to understand their words.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} When it was realized that Malinche was able to converse with the emissaries, she and Aguilar were set aside by Cort\u00e9s, who, according to G\u00f3mara, promised her \u201cmore than liberty\u201d if she would assist him in finding and communicating with Moctezuma.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=40\u201341}} Cort\u00e9s took Malinche back from Puertocarrero,{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} who was later given another indigenous woman before he was sent back to Spain.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=53}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=7}} Through Aguilar and Malinche, Cort\u00e9s talked with Moctezuma's emissaries. The emissaries also brought artists to make paintings of Malinche, Cort\u00e9s, and the rest of the group, as well as their ships and weapons, to be sent as records for Moctezuma.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=42}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=67}} D\u00edaz later said that the Nahuas also addressed Cort\u00e9s as \"Malinche\";{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}} they apparently took her as a point of reference for the group.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=56, 242}}{{efn|D\u00edaz explained this phenomenon by positing that \u201cMalinche\u201d in reference to Cort\u00e9s as a shorthand for \u201cMarina's Captain\u201d, because she was always in his company.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=293\u2013294}} However, according to Townsend, [[possessive]] construction in Nahuatl cannot be shortened that way. Moreover, D\u00edaz's theory cannot explain the usage of the name \u201cMalinche\u201d to refer to another Spaniard by the name of Juan Perez de Arteaga,{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=56, 242}} who was learning Nahuatl from her.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=22}}}}\n\nFrom then on, Malinche would work together with Aguilar to bridge communication between the Spaniards and the Nahuas;{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|pp=299\u2013301}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=42}} Cort\u00e9s would speak Spanish with Aguilar, who then translated into Yucatec Maya for Malinche, who in turn translated into Nahuatl, before reversing the process.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=84\u201385}} The translation chain grew even longer when, after the emissaries left, they met the [[Totonac]]s,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=68, 70\u201371}} whose language was unintelligible to both Malinche and Aguilar. There, Malinche asked for Nahuatl interpreters.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=43}} Karttunen remarks that \"it is a wonder any communication was accomplished at all\", for Cort\u00e9s's Spanish words had to be translated into Maya, Nahuatl, and [[Totonac languages|Totonac]] before reaching the locals, whose answers then went back through the same chain.{{sfn|Karttunen|1997|p=303}} From the meeting with the Totonacs, Cort\u00e9s learned of those who were hostile to Moctezuma.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=43}} According to the anthropologist and historian [[Ross Hassig]], this meeting was also a major turning point that \"set Cort\u00e9s's course irrevocably towards conquest\".{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=68, 70\u201371}} After securing an alliance with the Totonacs and founding the town of Villa Rica de la Vera Cruz, they started the march towards Tenochtitlan.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=73\u201374, 77}}\n\nThe first major polity that they encounter on the way to Tenochtitlan was [[Tlaxcala (Nahua state)|Tlaxcala]].{{sfn|Townsend|2006|p=59}} Although the [[Tlaxcaltecs|Tlaxcalans]] were initially hostile to the Spaniards and their allies,{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=79}} they later permitted the Spaniards to enter the city.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=62\u201363}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=86\u201389}} The Tlaxcalans negotiated an alliance with the Spaniards through Malinche and Aguilar. Later Tlaxcalan records of this meeting feature scenes where Malinche appears prominent, bridging the communication between the two sides as the Tlaxcalans presented the Spaniards with gifts of food and noblewomen to cement the alliance.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=69\u201372}} After several days in Tlaxcala, Cort\u00e9s continued the journey to Tenochtitlan by the way of [[Cholula (Mesoamerican site)|Cholula]], accompanied by a large number of Tlaxcalan soldiers.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|p=93}}\n\nThe Spaniards were received at Cholula and housed for several days, until, as the Spaniards claimed, the Cholulans stopped giving them food, dug secret pits, built a barricade around the city, and hid a large Aztec army in the outskirt in preparation for an attack against the Spaniards.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|pp=8\u20139}} Somehow, the Spaniards learned of this plot, and, in a [[preemptive strike]], assembled and [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire#Massacre of Cholula|massacred the Cholulans]].{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}} Later accounts specifically claimed that the plot was uncovered by Malinche. According to the version provided by D\u00edaz, she was approached by a Cholulan noblewoman who promised her a marriage to the woman's son if she were to switch side. Malinche, pretending to go along with the suggestion, learned from the woman about the plot, and reported all the details to Cort\u00e9s.{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=10}}{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}} This story has often been cited as an example of Malinche's \u201cbetrayal\u201d to her people.{{sfn|Karttunen|2001|p=353}} However, the veracity of the story has been questioned by modern historians such as Hassig and Townsend.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=81\u201382}} It has been suggested that the Tlaxcalans were the real mastermind behind the massacre. Cholula had previously supported Tlaxcala before joining the Aztec Empire one or two years prior, and losing them as an ally was a hard hit for the Tlaxcalans, whose state was now completely encircled by the Aztecs.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=81\u201382}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=210}} It is possible that the attack on the Cholulans was in fact a test from the Tlaxcalans for the Spaniards' trustworthiness.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=43, 94\u201396}}{{sfn|Restall|2018|p=210}} In this view, thus, Malinche's \u201cheroic\u201d discovery of the purported plot is only a part of the justification for the massacre.{{sfn|Hassig|2006|pp=97\u201398}}\n\n[[File:Cortez & La Malinche.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.5|The meeting of Cort\u00e9s and Moctezuma II, with Malinche acting as interpreter.]]\nThe combined forces reached Tenochtitlan in early November 1519, and was met by Moctezuma in a causeway leading to the city.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=77}} Malinche was in the middle of this event, translating the conversation between Cort\u00e9s and Moctezuma.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}} Gomara writes that Moctezuma was \"speaking through Malinche and Aguilar\", although other records indicate that Malinche was already translating directly,{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=82}} as she had quickly learned some Spanish herself.{{sfn|Restall|2003|p=83}}{{sfn|Townsend|2019|pp=99, 243}} Moctezuma's flowery speech delivered through Malinche at the meeting has been claimed by the Spaniards to represent a submission, but this interpretation is not followed by modern historians.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}} The deferential nature of the speech can be explained by Moctezuma's usage of {{lang|nah|tecpillahtolli}}, a Nahuatl register known for its indirection and complex set of reverential affixes.{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}}{{sfn|Karttunen|1994|p=11}} Despite Malinche's apparent ability to understand {{lang|nah|tecpillahtolli}}, it is possible that some nuances were lost in translation,{{sfn|Restall|2003|pp=97\u201398}} and the Spanish, deliberately or not, may have misinterpreted Moctezuma's actual words.{{sfn|Townsend|2006|pp=86\u201388}}\n\nFollowing the fall of Tenochtitl\u00e1n in late 1521 and the birth of her son [[Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s (son of do\u00f1a Marina)|Mart\u00edn Cort\u00e9s]] in 1522, Marina stayed in a house Cort\u00e9s built for her in the town of Coyoac\u00e1n, eight miles south of Tenochtitl\u00e1n, the Aztec capital city, while it was being rebuilt as Mexico City. Cort\u00e9s took Marina to quell a rebellion in [[Honduras]] in 1524\u20131526 when she is seen serving again as interpreter (suggestive of a knowledge of Maya dialects beyond Chontal and Yucat\u00e1n.) While in the mountain town of Orizaba in central Mexico, she married [[Juan Jaramillo]], a Spanish [[Hidalgo (Spanish nobility)|hidalgo]].<ref>Gordon, Helen. ''Voice of the Vanquished: The Story of the Slave Marina and Hernan Cort\u00e9s''. Chicago: University Editions, 1995, page 454.</ref>  Historians such as [[William H. Prescott|Prescott]] generally lost track of Marina after her journey to Central America. Some contemporary scholars have estimated that she died less than a decade after the conquest of Mexico-Tenochtitlan at some point in 1529.<ref>Chaison, Joanne. \"Mysterious Malinche: A Case of Mistaken Identity,\" ''The Americas'' 32, N. 4 (1976).</ref> Historian [[Hugh Thomas (historian)|Hugh Thomas]], in his book ''Conquest'', reports the probable date of her death as 1551, deduced from letters he discovered in Spain alluding to her as alive in 1550 and deceased after 1551.{{sfn|Thomas|1993|p=769}} She was survived by her son Don Mart\u00edn, who would be raised primarily by his father's family, and a daughter Do\u00f1a Mar\u00eda, who would be raised by Jaramillo and his second wife Do\u00f1a Beatriz de Andrada.<ref>Camilla Townsend, ''Malintzin's Choices: An Indian Woman in the Conquest of Mexico.'' University of New Mexico Press, 2006, pp. 168\u2013187.</ref>\n\n=== Role of La Malinche in the conquest of Mexico ===\n[[File:Malinche Tlaxcala.jpg|thumb|right|La Malinche and Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s in the city of Xaltelolco, in a drawing from the late 16th-century [[Aztec codices|codex]] ''[[History of Tlaxcala]]'']]\nFor the [[conquistador]]es, having a reliable interpreter was important enough, but there is evidence that Marina's role and influence were larger still. [[Bernal D\u00edaz del Castillo]], a soldier who, as an old man, produced the most comprehensive of the eye-witness accounts, the ''[[Historia verdadera de la conquista de la Nueva Espa\u00f1a]]'' (\"True Story of the Conquest of New Spain\"), speaks repeatedly and reverentially of the \"great lady\" Do\u00f1a Marina (always using the honorific title Do\u00f1a). \"Without the help of Do\u00f1a Marina\", he writes, \"we would not have understood the language of New Spain and Mexico.\" [[Rodr\u00edguez de Oca\u00f1a]], another conquistador, relates Cort\u00e9s' assertion that after God, Marina was the main reason for his success.\n\nThe evidence from indigenous sources is even more interesting, both in the commentaries about her role, and in her prominence in the codex drawings made of conquest events. Although to some Marina may be known as a traitor, she was not viewed as such by all the Tlaxcalan. In some depictions they portrayed her as \"larger than life\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |title=Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico |last=Townsend |first=Camilla |publisher=University of New Mexico Press |location=New Mexico |year=2006 |pages=74\u201376 |isbn=0-8263-3405-9}}</ref> sometimes larger than Cort\u00e9s, in rich clothing, and an alliance is shown between her and the Tlaxcalan instead of them and the Spaniards. They respected and trusted her and portrayed her in this light generations after the Spanish conquest.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the ''[[History of Tlaxcala|Lienzo de Tlaxcala (History of Tlaxcala)]]'', for example, not only is Cort\u00e9s rarely portrayed without Marina poised by his side, but she is shown at times on her own, seemingly directing events as an independent authority. If she had been trained for court life, as in D\u00edaz's account, her relationship to Cort\u00e9s may have followed the familiar pattern of marriage among native elite classes. The role of the Nahua wife acquired through an alliance would have been to assist her husband achieve his military and diplomatic objectives.<ref>Restall, Matthew. Seven Myths of the Spanish Conquest</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mesolore.org/viewer/view/2/Lienzo-de-Tlaxcala |title=Mesolore: A research & teaching tool on Mesoamerica |website=www.mesolore.org}}</ref>\n\nToday's historians give great credit to Marina's diplomatic skills, with some \"almost tempted to think of her as the real conqueror of Mexico.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Brandon |first=William |title=The Rise and Fall of North American Indians |year=2003 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart Publishers |location=Lanham, MD |page=88 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lde5K93ozuMC&pg=PA88&lpg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In fact, old conquistadors on various occasions would remember that one of her greatest skills had been her ability to convince other Indians of what she herself could see clearly, which was that it was useless in the long run to stand against Spanish metal and Spanish ships. In contrast with earlier parts of D\u00edaz del Castillo's account, after Marina's diplomacy began assisting Cort\u00e9s, the Spanish were forced into combat on one more occasion.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brandon |first=William |title=The Rise and Fall of North American Indians |year=2003 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart Publishers |location=Lanham, MD |page=88 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lde5K93ozuMC&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nHad La Malinche not been part of the Conquest of Mexico for her linguistic gift, communication between the Spanish and the Indigenous would have been much harder. La Malinche knew to speak in different registers and tones between certain Indigenous tribes and people. For the Nahua audiences, she spoke rhetorically, formally, and high-handedly. This shift into formality gave the Nahua the impression that she was a noblewoman who knew what she was talking about.<ref>Townsend, Camilla (2006). Malintzin's choices: an Indian woman in the conquest of Mexico. New Mexico: University of New Mexico Press. pp.58</ref>\n\n== Malinche\u2019s image in contemporary Mexico ==\n[[File:Monumento al Mestizaje.jpg|thumb|Modern statue of Cort\u00e9s, Marina, and their son Mart\u00edn, which was moved from a prominent place of display to an obscure one, due to protests]]\n\nMalinche's image has become a mythical [[archetype]] that [[Hispanic America]]n artists have represented in various forms of art. Her figure permeates historical, cultural, and social dimensions of Hispanic American cultures.{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=Intro.}} In modern times and in several genres, she is compared with the [[La Llorona]] (folklore story of the woman weeping for lost children), and the Mexican [[soldaderas]] (women who fought beside men during the [[Mexican Revolution]])<ref>Salas{{Page needed|date=October 2010}}</ref> for their brave actions.\n\nLa Malinche's legacy is one of myth mixed with legend, and the opposing opinions of the Mexican people about the legendary woman. Some see her as a founding figure of the Mexican nation, while others continue to see her as a traitor\u2014as may be assumed from a legend that she had a twin sister who went North, and from the pejorative [[nickname]] ''[[La Chingada]]'' associated with her twin.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nFeminist interventions into the figure of Malinche began in 1960s. The work of [[Rosario Castellanos]] was particularly significant; Chicanas began to refer to her as a \"mother\" as they adopted her as symbolism for duality and complex identity.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Castellanos |first=Rosario |title=Otra vez Sor Juana\" (\"Once Again Sor Juana\") |date=1963}}</ref> Castellanos's subsequent poem \"La Mallinche\" recast her not as a traitor but as a victim.<ref name=\"Romero2005\">{{cite book |author=Rolando Romero |title=Feminism, Nation and Myth: La Malinche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dfesWiXwkdQC&pg=PA28 |date=2005-01-01 |publisher=Arte Publico Press |isbn=978-1-61192-042-0 |pages=28\u2013 }}</ref> Mexican feminists defended Malinche as a woman caught between cultures, forced to make complex decisions, who ultimately served as a mother of a new race.<ref name=\"CoerverPasztor2004\">{{cite book |author1=Don M. Coerver |author2=Suzanne B. Pasztor |author3=Robert Buffington |title=Mexico: An Encyclopedia of Contemporary Culture and History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSred4NyOKoC&pg=PA200 |year=2004 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-57607-132-8 |pages=200\u2013 }}</ref>\n\nToday in Mexican Spanish, the words ''[[malinchism]]o''  and ''malinchista'' are used to denounce Mexicans who are perceived as denying their own cultural heritage by preferring foreign cultural expressions.<ref>Fortes De Leff, J. (2002). Racism in Mexico: Cultural Roots and Clinical Interventions1. Family Process, 41(4), 619-623.</ref>\n\nSome historians believe that La Malinche saved her people from the Aztecs, who held a hegemony throughout the territory and demanded tribute from its inhabitants.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Some Mexicans also credit her with having brought Christianity to the New World from Europe, and for having influenced Cort\u00e9s to be more humane than he would otherwise have been. It is argued, however, that without her help, Cort\u00e9s would not have been successful in conquering the Aztecs as quickly, giving the Aztec people enough time to adapt to new technology and methods of warfare. From that viewpoint, she is seen as one who betrayed the indigenous people by siding with the Spaniards. Recently a number of feminist Latinas have decried such a categorization as [[scapegoating]].{{sfn|Cypess|1991|p=12}}\n\nPresident [[Jos\u00e9 L\u00f3pez Portillo]] commissioned a sculpture of Cort\u00e9s, Do\u00f1a Marina, and their son Mart\u00edn, which was placed in front of Cort\u00e9s's house in the [[Coyoacan]] section of Mexico City.  Once L\u00f3pez Portillo left office, the sculpture was removed to an obscure park in the capital.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-03-31-wr-223-story.html/ It is time to stop vilifying the \"Spanish father of Mexico\"], accessed 10 June 2019</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:La Malinche statue.jpg|right|thumb|La Malinche, as part of the ''Monumento al Mestizaje'' in Mexico City]]\n\n*A reference to La Malinche as Marina is made in the novel ''[[The Manuscript Found in Saragossa]]'' by the Polish author [[Jan Potocki]], in which she is cursed for yielding her \"heart and her country to the hateful Cortez, chief of the sea-brigands.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Potocki |first=Jan |title=The Manuscript Found at Saragossa |year=1995 |publisher=Penguin Books |author2=trans. Ian Maclean}}</ref>\n*La Malinche appears in the adventure novel ''[[Montezuma's Daughter]]'' (1893) by [[Henry Rider Haggard|H. Rider Haggard]].\n*Do\u00f1a Marina appears in the Henry King film adventure ''[[Captain from Castile (novel)|Captain from Castile]]'' (1947) played Estela Inda.\n*La Malinche is portrayed as a Christian and protector of her fellow native Mexicans in the novel ''Tlaloc Weeps for Mexico'' (1939) by [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Passuth]], and is the main protagonist in such works as the novels ''The Golden Princess'' (1954) by [[Alexander Baron]] and ''Feathered Serpent: A Novel of the Mexican Conquest'' (2002) by [[Colin Falconer (writer)|Colin Falconer]]. In contrast, she is portrayed as a duplicitous traitor in [[Gary Jennings]]' novel ''[[Aztec (novel)|Aztec]]'' (1980). A novel published in 2006 by [[Laura Esquivel]] portrays the main character as a pawn of history who becomes ''Malinche''.\n*In 1949, choreographer Jos\u00e9 Lim\u00f3n premiered the dance trio \"La Milanche\" to music by Norman Lloyd. It was the first work created by Lim\u00f3n for his own company, and was based on his memories as a child of Mexican fiestas.<ref>[http://limon.org/dances/ \"Repertory\"] ''Lim\u00f3n''</ref>\n*The story of La Malinche is told in ''Cortez and Marina'' (1963) by [[Edison Marshall]].\n*In the 1973 Mexican film ''Leyendas macabras de la colonia'', La Malinche's mummy is in the possession of Luisa, her daughter by Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s, while her spirit inhabits a cursed painting.\n*La Malinche is referred to in the songs \"[[Cortez the Killer]]\" from the 1975 album ''[[Zuma (album)|Zuma]]'' by [[Neil Young]], and \"La Malinche\" by the French band [[Feu! Chatterton]] from their 2015 album ''Ici le jour (a tout enseveli)''\n*In the animated television series ''[[The Mysterious Cities of Gold]]'' (1982), which chronicles the adventures of a Spanish boy and his companions traveling throughout South America in 1532 to seek the lost city of [[El Dorado]], a woman called Marinche becomes a dangerous adversary. The series was originally produced in Japan, and then translated into English.\n*In the fictional ''[[Star Trek]]'' universe, a starship, the USS ''Malinche'', was named for La Malinche, and appeared in the 1997 \"[[For the Uniform]]\" episode of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''. This was done by [[Hans Beimler (screenwriter)|Hans Beimler]], a native of [[Mexico City]], who together with friend [[Robert Hewitt Wolfe]] later wrote a screenplay based on La Malinche called ''The Serpent and the Eagle''.\n*La Malinche is a key character in the opera ''[[La Conquista (opera)|La Conquista]]'' (2005) by Italian composer [[Lorenzo Ferrero]].\n*Malinalli is the main character in a 2011 historical novel by Helen Heightsman Gordon, ''Malinalli of the Fifth Sun: The Slave Girl Who Changed the Fate of Mexico and Spain''.\n*Author [[Octavio Paz]] addresses the issue of La Malinche's role as the mother of Mexican culture in ''[[The Labyrinth of Solitude]]''. He uses her relation to Cort\u00e9s symbolically to represent Mexican culture as originating from rape and violation.\n*Malinal is a character in [[Graham Hancock]]'s series of novels ''War God: Nights of the Witch'' (2013) and ''War God: Return of the Plumed Serpent'' (2014), which is a fictional story describing the events related to the Hernan Cort\u00e9s' expedition to Mexico and the Spanish conquest of the Aztec empire.\n*Malinche is a character in Edward Rickford's ''The Serpent and the Eagle'', referred to variously as ''Dona Marina'' and ''Malintze''. The depiction of her character was praised by historical novelists and bloggers.\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Mexico|Biography}}\n*[[Felipillo]]\n*[[History of Mexico]]\n*[[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire]]\n*[[Women in Mexico]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n: {{cite book |last=Chapman |first=Anne M. |author-link=Anne Chapman |editor1=Karl Polanyi |editor2=Conrad M. Arensberg |editor3=Harry W. Pearson |year=1957 |chapter=Port of Trade Enclaves in Aztec and Maya Civilizations |title=Trade and Market in the Early Empires: Economies in History and Theory |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Cypess |first=Sandra Messinger |year=1991 |title=La Malinche in Mexican Literature: From History to Myth |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin, TX |isbn=9780292751347 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Downs |first=Kristina |year=2008 |title=Mirrored Archetypes: The Contrasting Cultural Roles of La Malinche and Pocahontas |journal=[[Western Folklore]] |volume=67 |issue=4 |pages=397\u2013414 |publisher=Western States Folklore Society |jstor=25474939 |location=Long Beach, CA |issn=0043-373X |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Evans |first=Susan Toby |year=2004 |title=Ancient Mexico & Central America: Archaeology and Culture History |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |location=London |isbn=9780500284407 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Franco |first=Jean |author-link=Jean Franco |editor1=Mary Louise Pratt |editor2=Kathleen Newman |year=1999 |chapter=La Malinche: from gift to sexual contract |title=Critical Passions: Selected Essays |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |location=Durham, NC |isbn=9780822322481 |pp=66\u201382 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Hassig |first=Ross |author-link=Ross Hassig |year=2006 |title=Mexico and the Spanish Conquest |publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]] |location=Norman, OK |isbn=9780806182087 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Herrera-Sobek |first=Mar\u00eda |editor1=Rolando J. Romero |editor2=Amanda Nolacea Harris |y